body:
Hello All!

Take the following snippit

``` javascript
   //component
   export default React.createClass({
      getInitialState: function() {
         return {
            error: "",
            valid: true
         }
      },
      isValid: function() {
         return this.state.valid;
      },
      setValid: function(isValid) {
         this.setState({
            valid: isValid
         });
      },
      //...
      render: function() {
         return (
            <div className="myComponent">
               <input className={this.state.valid ? "valid" : ""} size=20 />
               <span className={this.state.valid ? "valid" : ""}>{this.state.error}</span>
            </div>
         )
      }
   })
   //Parent
   export default React.createClass({
      handleClick: function() {
         var comp = this.refs.comp;

         comp.setValid(false)
         comp.setError("Needs a value");
      },
      render: function() {
         return (
            <div>
               <MyComponent ref="comp"/>
               <button onClick={this.handleClick}>Click</button>
            </div>
         )
      }
   })
```

Before the update to refs, where it passed back the React component, i was able to access helper methods on this class to handle certain pieces of state, like if the component was valid, or what error message is being displayed. Now in 0.14, it actually returns the DOM node. I understand that everything can be done in javascript to modify the DOM (i.e. Take the message and just change the node's innerHTML to the message), it just adds extra that must be done that i feel was a good fit for modifying the state. Is this way of thinking more of an anti-pattern, or was this not considered due to not seeing many people accomplishing this sort of thing?
